<p style="text-align:justify;">since leaving the Missisouri.  From the state of the Groun<span class="DelHand-author">g</span><span class="AddHand-author">d</span> we could judge that Buffaloes in astonishing numbers make this quarter their constant residence &#8212; the grass was eaten up and the ground ploughed with their feet<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Came to a high hill, from whence we expected to see the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Schians &#8212;</span> but <span class="AddHand-author">we </span>w<span class="DelHand-author">h</span>ere dis-appointed.  They were not where our Conductor left them, and this disappointment caused a suspicion of treachery.  The arrival of reinforcements at the camp of the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Schians</span> it was thought might encourage that nation to lye in ambuscade in a small wood which was in our <span style="text-decoration:underline;">route</span>.  It was therefore considered as advis<span class="DelHand-author">e</span>able to keep possession of the Hill and send a party of Young men well mounted a head <span style="text-decoration:underline;">en decouv</span><span class="AddHand-author"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">ete</span></span>.  The <span style="text-decoration:underline;">schian</span> who had accompany<span class="DelHand-author">ied</span><span class="AddHand-author">ed</span> our Conducter was detained and the poor fellow seemed very uneasy as were I believe most of us<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  After remaining in a state of Suspence for a while the Young m<span class="DelHand-author">a</span><span class="AddHand-author">e</span>n made sign<span class="DelHand-author">e</span>s and we moved forward with great speed.  A little river which passed at the foot of the Hill gave us great trouble to ford.  Soft and muddy the horses went up to their bellies in mire and some of them stuck fast until</p>
